      <h1><a href="/factsheets/default.aspx">Fact Sheets</a>: Corridor Management Initiatives</h1>
      
      <p>Corridor management initiatives (CMI) are extremely important exercises that bring together multiple stakeholders to develop solutions, combine funding, and improve freight corridor management.   Similar to noise roundtables and other community forums, CMIs also provide opportunities to engage local communities through committee membership and create educational outreach about the value of freight to the local, regional, and national economy.    Through their educational element, CMIs also provide opportunities for local and regional planning organizations to better consider freight as they develop comprehensive plans and adopt zoning amendments to ensure land use incompatibilities can be reduced in the future.  Examples of single state, multi-state and private sector CMIs are provided below.</p>

<h2>Single State Corridor Management Initiatives</h2>

<p>Vermont created a <a href="http://www.aot.state.vt.us/planning/VTcorridor.htm">Corridor Management Handbook</a> (CMH) in 2005 to provide a technical resource for state and regional agency planners and their consultants who are undertaking development of transportation corridor management plans.  The CMH was also considered to be helpful for a broader set of people who are involved in corridor planning efforts - local officials; planning, zoning, and public works staff; transit service providers; corridor residents and business people; and other interested parties.</p>

<p>According to the Vermont Agency of Transportation:</p>  

<p class="quote">The idea for this handbook grew out of the recognition that many of Vermont's transportation needs can be most effectively addressed at the corridor level rather than on a piecemeal basis. Limited resources for transportation improvements at all levels of government are dictating more creative and collaborative approaches to solving - and preventing transportation problems.  A corridor approach offers the opportunity for communities to collectively plot a future strategy which makes the best possible use of available resources, takes advantage of synergies to produce the best outcomes, and has a greater chance of becoming a reality - than would otherwise be the case if each community acted on its own.</p>

<p>Chicago’s <a href="http://www.createprogram.org/">CREATE</a> initiative is another multi-year project centered in a single state.   Begun in 2003, the project is currently underway. As of 2010, ten projects have been completed.  CREATE is a  partnership between the U.S. DOT, the State of Illinois, the City of Chicago, Metra, Amtrak, and all the Class I railroads.  Railroad partners contributed $100 million to the initiative in 2005, and the highway trust fund legislation authorized $100 million for CREATE in 2005.  The first federal funding for the initiative was released in 2007, and in 2010 CREATE received high speed rail funds and American Recovery Reinvestment Act TIGER grants.</p>  

<p>CREATE will invest in infrastructure improvements to improve the efficiency of the rail infrastructure in the Chicago region.  This is expected to reduce the congestion and train delays that Chicago currently contends with, and also mitigate some of the environmental impacts from freight.   CREATE is focusing on multiple corridors that intersect and create the freight network within the Chicago area.   The CREATE program comprises the following projects:</p>
<ul>
<li>254 road/rail grade separations</li>
<li>6 passenger/freight rail grade separations</li>
<li>Railroad projects to improve rail infrastructure and upgrade technologies</li>
<li>Viaduct improvement program</li>
<li>Grade crossing safety enhancements</li>
<li>Rail operations and visibility improvements</li>
</ul>
<p>Established in 1998, the <a href="http://www.psrc.org/transportation/freight/fast/">Freight Action Strategy for the Everett-Seattle Tacoma Corridor (FAST) Partnership</a>, has been pursuing funding for twenty-five high-priority projects for transportation improvements along the railroad mainline and truck corridors near the Puget Sound ports between Everett and Tacoma.  Fourteen projects have been completed with additional projects underway.</p>  

<p>FAST is a partnership of state, local, and regional agencies, including Puget Sound ports, railroads, and the trucking industry. Its goals are to:</p>
<ul>
<li>Improve mainline rail capacity and connectivity</li>
<li>Eliminate roadway chokepoints where rail and arterial roads intersect</li>
<li>Provide safe rail crossings in communities</li>
<li>Establish reliable truck links between ports, rail yards, and freight distribution centers.</li>
</ul>  

<p>The Port of Seattle committed to contributing about $30 million to the program. To date, it has authorized about $14 million of contributions for FAST corridor partners' projects.</p> 

<p><a href="http://www.tampabayfreight.com/"Tampa Bay Regional Goods Movement Study</a> was initiated by Florida’s Department of Transportation District 7.  A website was created to provide local government, freight stakeholders, and the public with information regarding freight.  As part of this project a <a href="http://www.tampabayfreight.com/database/database.html">Regional Goods Movement Database</a> was developed.  A freight corridor screening process and guidelines were also developed to evaluate the use of the state highways and other highways in the Tampa Bay area.  The freight corridor screening methodology can be seen in Figure 1.</p>
