<h2>Multi-State Corridor Initiatives</h2>

<p>There have been many multi-state CMIs over the years, but only one has a distinctly freight focus.  The I-10 National Freight Corridor Study was initiated in 2001 and managed by the transportation agencies in the eight states through which I-10 traverses. A comprehensive evaluation of the overall corridor system was conducted.  The study assessed the need for, and feasibility of, a broad range of options to facilitate the movement of goods along the corridor.  The study:</p>
<ul>  
<li>Gathered information about freight movement</li> 
<li>Inventoried the physical condition of the interstate</li> 
<li>Identified operational problems for all motorists on I-10, and</li> 
<li>Determined what improvements can be made to ease congestion and enhance safety.</li>
</ul> 

<p>The study also gathered information about how truck traffic along I-10 affects air quality, highway safety, road maintenance, and the economies and job markets in the communities linked to the corridor. Although the study focused primarily on freight movement along I-10, consideration was given to roadways that feed I-10 from large freight moving areas, such as manufacturing and distribution centers, sea ports, air cargo facilities, and railroad intermodal yards.  This project created an <a href="http://www.i10freightstudy.org/">interactive tour</a> where visitors to the website can find the major metro areas served by I-10 and the port, airports and rail facility freight components.  Not only are such tools extremely important both from a corridor management perspective, but they also to educate the general public, and other local planning officials about the working of the corridor’s freight transportation system.   The I-10 study has taken a long-term view of corridor management.  The multi-state study began phasing in recommended strategies in 2008 and this is planned to continue till 2025.</p> 

<h2>Private Sector Initiatives</h2>

<p>The <a href="http://www.nascocorridor.com/">North American Super Corridor Coalition, Inc (NASCO)</a> was created in 1994 to unite public and private sectors to address critical national and international trade, transportation, security, and environmental issues.   Following the I-35 corridor through the central United States, and into eastern and central Canada and Mexico, the initiative covers a multi-modal transportation network that connects 71 million people and over a $1 trillion dollars in commerce between the three nations.</p>  

<p>NASCO members include cities, counties, states, provinces, and the private sector from all three countries.   NASCO hosts committees in its three main focus areas.</p>
<ul>
<li>Transportation Efficiency and Security</li>
<li>Energy and Environmental Quality</li>
<li>Entry-level Logistics Workforce Development</li>
</ul>

<p>The Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railroad rolled out its <a href="http://www.corridorsofcommerce.com/explore-the-corridors/">Corridors of Commerce</a> initiative in 2010.   This website provides information on the benefits of rail, the three major corridors of the BNSF network (Mid Continent Corridor, Great Northern Corridor and the Transcon), and other information regarding railroad corridors.  BNSF will work with the public sector to expand and improve these corridors of commerce. This will include improvements to relieve chokepoints on the national rail system.</p>  

<p>Another Railroad that is extremely active in CMI’s is the <a href="http://www.ncrr.com/">North Carolina Railroad (NCRR)</a>.   Established by Charter of the North Carolina State Legislature in 1849 it operates a 317 mile corridor.  Norfolk Southern and Amtrak runs trains over the NCRRs right of way.   The NCRR has a <a href="http://www.ncrr.com/ncrr-corridor-brochure.pdf">Corridor Management Brochure</a>, and is actively involved in over eleven corridor management initiatives, including mapping, notification, educational outreach about the corridor, and working with local jurisdictions.</p> 

          
